snippet.textDisplay:
I'm not one to really watch these videos, but I will do my best to stay objective and list some personal suggestions, or maybe questions...hope they help:
1. The colors that you use in this seem like they would work well for costume, or for extravagance, but not everyday application. In theatre, it would be used to amplify the expressions so they can be more readable.
2. I would personally say more is less. Maybe it's from me being a naturalist and seeing women as beautiful w/o makeup. I personally see you in this way.
3. I would also so that if the pallette offers you the flexibility to travel along the spectrum w/o much trouble, it's going the right way. I think this may go back to what I said about brilliant color. It's tough to beat it as it's already so intense.

I know your video is your opinion, and I'm just stating mine. Hope this springs some ideas.

I think the reason the colors might have been so pigmented is because of the way you applied them. Most people don't pack on a shadow in the same area and then blend the edges, they usually will just go right into blending it out. So not to say the palette isn't good or I don't trust you, I do 100%, just I think people may get a different result than you did.

Love the two looks a lot. ❤❤❤
